The government approved, on Wednesday, "The National Immigration Strategy 2015-2018" and "The Action Plan for the current year", documents considered to be "another stage that Romania is pursuing in the process of modernising the immigration management process on national territory", according to a press release.
The above-mentioned source shows that the strategy aims to effectively manage the phenomenon of immigration, including general strategic objectives, specific objectives and action guidelines that reflect policies established at European level, adapted to national realities.
In view of the problems faced by the States of the immediate vicinity of Romania, measures are being taken to manage the unitary and coherent situations caused by the possible emergence of an influx of illegal immigrants into Romania, resulting from situations of political, social, economic or military crisis.
"Roman authorities will contribute to the creation of a flexible admission system, but at the same time, they will pay particular attention to citizens from countries with potential migration or which may prejudice national security," adds the above source.
The strategy identifies a number of factors that can influence immigration and asylum, including maintaining the conflict situation in Syria, reactivating the conflict in Iraq, maintaining an unstable situation in the neighbouring areas of Romania (Ukraine, Transnistria), perpetuating and increasing the intensity of the Israeli-Palestinian armed conflict.
On the other hand, the document sets out a number of general strategic objectives related to immigration, such as: promoting legal migration, more rigorous controls on the legality of the residence of third-country nationals in Romania and the corresponding application of removal measures and restrictive measures, improving the national asylum system.
The national strategy also includes specific objectives relevant to the transposition and implementation of the general strategic objectives.
These include: facilitating access on Romanian territory to third-country citizens who respond to labour force needs, promoting access to third-country citizens to Romanian higher education institutions for the areas and professions identified as deficits.
With regard to the 2015 Action Plan, the Government appreciates that it is "a means by which concrete activities are established leading to the creation of a flexible system to stop the growing migration phenomenon".
